\begin{abstract}
\noindent
The Koide relation $Q = (\sum m_\ell)/(\sum \sqrt{m_\ell})^2 = 2/3$ for the charged leptons has held to one part in $10^5$ for over forty years without an accepted derivation. As shown by Kocik~\cite{Kocik2012}, this relation has a geometric interpretation: identifying the lepton mass square roots with the Descartes curvatures of three mutually tangent circles, the Koide relation is the precise condition under which the algebraically natural combination $e_1 - \sqrt{p_2} = (\sum \sqrt{m_\ell}) - \sqrt{\sum m_\ell}$ coincides with the geometrically determined outer Soddy curvature $e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}$. We compute this curvature, denote it $\mathcal{F}$, and observe that $\mathcal{F}^2 = 95.113$~MeV reproduces the strange-quark $\msbar$ mass at the natural lepton-sum scale $\mu = \sum m_\ell$ within current lattice precision (residual $-0.019$~MeV against a total uncertainty of $\pm 0.814$~MeV). Under a log-uniform prior on Koide-saturating lepton triples, the observed match arises in $0.58\%$ of valid samples (95\% CI $[0.49\%,\,0.68\%]$), corresponding to approximately $7.4$ bits of structural compression beyond what the Koide constraint already provides. We present this as a structural observation, not a derivation or a prediction. We make no claim about an underlying mechanism. We disclose the order of operations leading to the observation, and we report scale sensitivity, input sensitivity, and a Koide-conditioned null-model analysis quantifying the residual look-elsewhere effect.
\end{abstract}

%======================================================================
\section{Introduction}
%======================================================================

The Koide relation~\cite{Koide1982,Koide1983}
\begin{equation}
Q \;\equiv\; \frac{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}{\big(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\big)^2} \;=\; \frac{2}{3}
\label{eq:koide}
\end{equation}
holds for the observed charged lepton pole masses to one part in $10^5$. Using the PDG~2024 values~\cite{PDG2024} ($m_e = 0.5109989$~MeV, $m_\mu = 105.6584$~MeV, $m_\tau = 1776.93 \pm 0.09$~MeV), one computes $Q = 0.666661$. The relation has resisted derivation since 1981; reviews and modern reinterpretations appear in~\cite{Foot1994,Sumino2009,Krolikowski2014}. We treat~(\ref{eq:koide}) as an empirical input.

In 2012, Kocik~\cite{Kocik2012} observed that the Koide relation has a Descartes-circle interpretation: identifying $k_i \equiv \sqrt{m_i}$ for $i \in \{e, \mu, \tau\}$, the lepton mass square roots are realizable as three of four curvatures of a mutually tangent Soddy circle configuration governed by the Descartes circle theorem. The Koide value $Q = 2/3$ is precisely the condition under which the algebraically natural combination $e_1 - \sqrt{p_2}$ formed from the leptons coincides with the geometrically determined outer Soddy curvature $e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}$ of the configuration. We make this statement precise as Proposition~\ref{prop:koide_descartes} below.

We extend Kocik's construction by one step. The outer Soddy curvature is determined uniquely (up to the binary inner/outer choice) once the three input curvatures are specified. We compute it for the observed lepton triple, denote it $\mathcal{F}$, and report a numerical observation: $\mathcal{F}^2$ equals the strange-quark $\msbar$ mass at the natural lepton-sum scale $\mu = \sum m_\ell$ within current lattice precision. We make no theoretical claim. The contribution of this paper is the computation of $\mathcal{F}$ within Kocik's framework and the disclosure of the resulting numerical match, together with a quantification of how unlikely such a match is under a Koide-conditioned prior.

%======================================================================
\section{The Koide relation as a Descartes condition}
%======================================================================

We summarize the Kocik construction~\cite{Kocik2012} for completeness and to fix notation.

The Descartes circle theorem~\cite{Coxeter1968} states that four mutually tangent circles in the plane, with curvatures $k_1, k_2, k_3, k_4$, satisfy
\begin{equation}
(k_1 + k_2 + k_3 + k_4)^2 \;=\; 2\,(k_1^2 + k_2^2 + k_3^2 + k_4^2).
\label{eq:descartes}
\end{equation}
Given three curvatures $k_1, k_2, k_3$, equation~(\ref{eq:descartes}) is a quadratic in $k_4$ with two real solutions
\begin{equation}
k_4^{\,\pm} \;=\; (k_1 + k_2 + k_3) \;\pm\; 2\sqrt{k_1 k_2 + k_2 k_3 + k_1 k_3},
\label{eq:soddy}
\end{equation}
corresponding respectively to the inner and outer Soddy circles tangent to the original three. By convention, the larger-curvature solution $k_4^{\,+}$ corresponds to the smaller circle (the inner Soddy circle, nestled in the gap between the original three), and the smaller-curvature solution $k_4^{\,-}$ corresponds to the larger circle (the outer Soddy circle, conventionally drawn enclosing the original three). The relevant quantity for our purposes is the outer curvature $k_4^{\,-} = e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}$.

\begin{proposition}[Koide and the outer Soddy curvature, after Kocik~\cite{Kocik2012}]
\label{prop:koide_descartes}
Identify $k_i \equiv \sqrt{m_i}$ for $i \in \{e, \mu, \tau\}$. Let $e_1 = \sum_i \sqrt{m_i}$, $e_2 = \sum_{i<j} \sqrt{m_i m_j}$, and $p_2 = \sum_i m_i$. The outer Soddy curvature of the Descartes configuration $(k_e, k_\mu, k_\tau)$ is
\begin{equation}
k_4^{\,-} \;=\; e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}.
\label{eq:k4_geometric}
\end{equation}
The algebraically simpler expression
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F} \;\equiv\; e_1 - \sqrt{p_2} \;=\; \big(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\big) - \sqrt{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}
\label{eq:F_alg}
\end{equation}
coincides with $k_4^{\,-}$ if and only if the Koide relation $Q \equiv p_2/e_1^2 = 2/3$ holds exactly.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
The Soddy form follows from solving the quadratic~(\ref{eq:descartes}) for $k_4$ given $k_1, k_2, k_3$, using the identity $e_1^2 = p_2 + 2 e_2$ to simplify the discriminant; the smaller-curvature root is $k_4^{\,-} = e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}$. Setting $e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2} = e_1 - \sqrt{p_2}$ yields $4 e_2 = p_2$. Combined with $e_1^2 = p_2 + 2 e_2$, this gives $e_1^2 = p_2 + p_2/2 = (3/2) p_2$, equivalently $p_2/e_1^2 = 2/3$, which is the Koide condition. Conversely, if $Q = 2/3$ then $e_2 = e_1^2/6 = p_2/4$, so $2\sqrt{e_2} = \sqrt{p_2}$ and the two expressions agree. \qed
\end{proof}

Proposition~\ref{prop:koide_descartes} gives the precise content of Kocik's geometric reading of Koide. The Koide relation is the statement that the dimensionally natural combination $e_1 - \sqrt{p_2}$, formed without reference to circles, is in fact the outer Soddy curvature of the Descartes configuration whose three input curvatures are the lepton mass square roots. The observed leptons satisfy $Q = 0.666661$, so the equality of~(\ref{eq:k4_geometric}) and~(\ref{eq:F_alg}) holds to one part in $10^5$. In what follows we use the form~(\ref{eq:F_alg}) for numerical convenience and treat $\mathcal{F}$ as the (Koide-approximate) outer Soddy curvature.

Although Kocik~\cite{Kocik2012} gives the geometric identification of Koide as a Descartes condition, to our knowledge the outer Soddy curvature $\mathcal{F}$ has not previously been computed and compared with hadronic observables.

%======================================================================
\section{The outer Soddy curvature of the lepton triple}
%======================================================================

We have defined $\mathcal{F}$ in equation~(\ref{eq:F_alg}). Two further remarks before computing it.

\paragraph{Uniqueness within Kocik's framework.}
$\mathcal{F}$ is not chosen from a catalog of symmetric polynomials. Once the Koide relation is read as a Descartes condition (Proposition~\ref{prop:koide_descartes}), the only natural Descartes-determined quantities of dimension $[\text{mass}]^{1/2}$ are the two Soddy curvatures $k_4^{\pm} = e_1 \pm 2\sqrt{e_2}$. The choice between them is binary (inner versus outer), not a continuous selection. We adopt the outer curvature, the smaller of the two and the one corresponding to the larger circle in the Descartes configuration. We discuss the role of this binary choice in the look-elsewhere accounting (Section~\ref{sec:robustness}).

\paragraph{Numerical value.}
At the PDG~2024 central charged-lepton pole masses,
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F} \;=\; 9.7528\;\text{MeV}^{1/2}, \qquad \mathcal{F}^2 \;=\; 95.1134\;\text{MeV}.
\label{eq:F_value}
\end{equation}
The propagated uncertainty from PDG lepton inputs is $\sigma_{\mathcal{F}^2} = 0.010$~MeV (Section~\ref{sec:robustness}), dominated by the tau mass uncertainty. The corresponding geometric quantity $k_4^{\,-} = e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}$ agrees with $\mathcal{F}$ to one part in $10^5$, the precision at which Koide holds.

%======================================================================
\section{The observation}
%======================================================================

Evaluate the strange-quark $\msbar$ mass at the natural lepton-sum scale,
\begin{equation}
\mu_\star \;\equiv\; m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau \;=\; 1883.1\;\text{MeV},
\end{equation}
by running the FLAG~2024 lattice average~\cite{FLAG2024} $m_s^{\msbar}(2~\text{GeV}) = 93.5 \pm 0.8$~MeV (for $N_f = 2{+}1{+}1$) via four-loop QCD~\cite{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$. This gives
\begin{equation}
m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star) \;=\; 95.132 \pm 0.814\;\text{MeV},
\end{equation}
where the uncertainty includes lattice input, the running of $\alpha_s$, and four-loop truncation, with the lattice contribution dominating. Comparing,
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}^2 - m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star) \;=\; -0.019\;\text{MeV},
\label{eq:residual}
\end{equation}
or about $-0.023$ standard deviations of the lattice uncertainty. The PDG~2024 value $m_s^{\msbar}(2~\text{GeV}) = 93.5 \pm 0.8$~MeV gives a numerically identical result; the agreement does not depend on the choice between FLAG and PDG averaging.

We deliberately avoid framing~(\ref{eq:residual}) as a precision-significance claim. The residual is small in units of the lattice uncertainty, but the meaningful question is not how many standard deviations separate $\mathcal{F}^2$ from $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$; it is whether the structural setup that produced $\mathcal{F}$ would, under a reasonable null, generically produce numbers near $m_s$ at the natural scale. We address that question in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}.

\paragraph{Methodological note on order of operations.}
We disclose the order of operations leading to this observation, because it bears on the look-elsewhere assessment in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}. The author was investigating Kocik's geometric reading~\cite{Kocik2012} of the Koide relation and computed the fourth (outer Soddy) curvature of the Koide-saturating lepton triple as a geometric question, with the original motivation being whether the missing fourth curvature might admit a particle interpretation. The numerical agreement $\mathcal{F}^2 \approx m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$ was noticed only after the geometric computation was complete, on comparison with a previously consulted reference value for the strange-quark mass. The function $\mathcal{F}$ was therefore not selected from a class of candidate symmetric polynomials of lepton masses; it was determined by Kocik's framework, and its specific power and evaluation scale were determined by dimensional consistency with the natural mass scale of the lepton triple. The null-model analysis in Section~\ref{sec:robustness} quantifies the residual selection freedom that remains after this structural narrowing.

%======================================================================
\section{Robustness}
\label{sec:robustness}
%======================================================================

We report four robustness checks: input sensitivity, scale sensitivity, a tight null-model test conditioned on the specific structural claim, and a loose null-model test admitting expanded look-elsewhere. All computations are reproducible from the open-source code accompanying this paper~\cite{KoideSoddyCode}.

\subsection{Input sensitivity}

Propagating PDG~2024 lepton uncertainties through~(\ref{eq:F_def}) yields $\sigma_{\mathcal{F}^2}^{\text{lepton}} = 0.010$~MeV, dominated by $\sigma_{m_\tau} = 0.09$~MeV. Combined in quadrature with the lattice running uncertainty $\sigma_{m_s} = 0.814$~MeV at $\mu_\star$, the lepton inputs contribute approximately $0.02\%$ of the total error budget; the remaining $99.98\%$ comes from the lattice strange-quark mass. The lepton side of~(\ref{eq:residual}) is essentially exact at present precision, and the test is dominated by lattice uncertainty.

\subsection{Scale sensitivity}

We compute $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu)$ for $\mu/\mu_\star \in [0.5, 4.0]$ and compare against the constant $\mathcal{F}^2$. The agreement degrades monotonically away from $\mu_\star$, with residual reaching $-30\sigma$ at $\mu = 0.5\,\mu_\star$. The intervals over which $|\mathcal{F}^2 - m_s^{\msbar}(\mu)|$ remains within one and two standard deviations of $\sigma_{m_s}(\mu)$ are
\begin{align}
\text{1$\sigma$ window:} \quad &\mu \in [1845,\,1940]\;\text{MeV} \;\;\approx\;\mu_\star (1 \pm 2.5\%),\\
\text{2$\sigma$ window:} \quad &\mu \in [1789,\,1996]\;\text{MeV} \;\;\approx\;\mu_\star (1 \pm 5.5\%).
\end{align}
The 1$\sigma$ window is narrow (about $\pm 2.5\%$), confirming that the relation is picking out a specific scale rather than holding broadly across hadronic energies. Crucially, $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ is exactly fixed by the lepton inputs, with no continuous adjustability: the agreement at $\mu_\star$ is not the result of choosing $\mu$ to optimize a fit, because $\mu_\star$ is determined by the same data ($m_e, m_\mu, m_\tau$) that determines $\mathcal{F}$.

\subsection{Tight null-model test}
\label{sec:null_tight}

The relevant question is: under a Koide-conditioned prior on lepton triples, how often does $\mathcal{F}^2$ land within current lattice precision of $m_s^{\msbar}$ at the natural scale of that triple? We construct the null as follows.

Sample candidate triples $(m_1, m_2, m_3)$ with $m_3$ drawn log-uniformly from $[10^0, 10^4]$~MeV, $m_1$ drawn log-uniformly from $[10^{-3}, 10^{-1}]\cdot m_3$, and $m_2$ solved analytically from the Koide condition $Q(m_1, m_2, m_3) = 2/3$ in the physical range $m_1 < m_2 < m_3$. Discard triples for which no real $m_2$ exists in this range. Verify $|Q - 2/3| < 10^{-5}$ for each retained triple. The sampling yields $25{,}485$ valid triples out of $10^5$ samples; the remaining samples were excluded because the natural scale $\mu_\star^{(i)} \equiv m_1 + m_2 + m_3$ fell below $1$~GeV, where four-loop QCD running is not reliable, so the test is undefined for those triples on methodological grounds rather than excluded post hoc.

For each valid triple, compute $\mathcal{F}^{(i)}$ and $\mu_\star^{(i)}$, run $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star^{(i)})$ from the FLAG 2~GeV input, and record a hit if $|\mathcal{F}^{(i)\,2} - m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star^{(i)})| < \sigma_{m_s}(\mu_\star^{(i)})$. Of $25{,}485$ valid triples, $147$ produced hits. The hit fraction is
\begin{equation}
p_{\text{tight}} \;=\; 0.5768\%, \qquad
95\%\text{ Clopper--Pearson CI:}\;[0.49\%,\,0.68\%].
\label{eq:tight_null}
\end{equation}

In information-theoretic terms, the relation compresses the strange-quark mass at lattice precision by approximately
\begin{equation}
-\log_2\!\big(p_{\text{tight}}\big) \;\approx\; 7.4\;\text{bits}
\end{equation}
beyond what the Koide constraint already provides. The distribution of $(\mathcal{F}^{(i)\,2} - m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star^{(i)}))/\sigma_{m_s}$ across the $25{,}485$ valid samples spans roughly $\pm 50$ standard deviations; the observed lepton triple sits within the central $\pm 1\sigma$ window, which is the rare outcome quantified by~(\ref{eq:tight_null}).

\subsection{Loose null-model test}
\label{sec:null_loose}

To bound the residual look-elsewhere effect across a broader claim, we test $\mathcal{F}^n$ for $n \in \{1, 2, 3\}$ against each of $\{m_u, m_d, m_s, m_c, m_b\}$ at the natural scale $\mu_\star^{(i)}$ of each triple, counting a triple as a hit if any of the $15$ comparisons agrees within current lattice $1\sigma$. Across the same $25{,}485$ valid triples, the overall hit fraction is
\begin{equation}
p_{\text{loose}} \;=\; 0.812\%, \qquad
95\%\text{ Clopper--Pearson CI:}\;[0.71\%,\,0.93\%],
\label{eq:loose_null}
\end{equation}
only marginally larger than $p_{\text{tight}}$. The breakdown by quark and integer power is shown in Table~\ref{tab:loose}. Up- and down-quark hits at $n = 1$ are physically excluded by mass dimension ($\mathcal{F}^1 \sim 10$~MeV is too large for $m_u, m_d$). Strange hits at $n = 2$ dominate, accounting for $147/207 \approx 71\%$ of all hits in the loose null. Charm hits at $n = 3$ and bottom hits at $n = 3$ exist for some triples in the prior, but the observed lepton triple is not among them: at $\mu_\star = 1883$~MeV, $\mathcal{F}^3 = 927.7$~MeV does not match $m_c^{\msbar}(\mu_\star) \approx 1100$~MeV nor $m_b^{\msbar}(\mu_\star) \approx 5300$~MeV. The observed triple sits specifically in the strange-at-$n{=}2$ channel and in no other.

