\subsection{Interpretation}

The tight null is the test most directly bearing on the structural claim of this paper: it asks how often the specific match $\mathcal{F}^2 \approx m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$ arises by chance in a Koide-saturating triple, given the structural narrowing already provided by Kocik's framework. The answer, $0.58\%$, corresponds to $7.4$ bits of compression. The loose null bounds the residual look-elsewhere effect when the binary choice between $k_4^{\pm}$, the integer-power choice $n \in \{1, 2, 3\}$, and the choice of comparison quark are all admitted as adjustable; it raises the effective hit fraction by roughly $40\%$, to $0.81\%$. Both numbers should be reported; the second is the honest upper bound on the structural significance after admitting all selection freedom we can identify.

%======================================================================
\section{What this is not}
%======================================================================

We make the following non-claims explicit, because the natural reading of a numerical match between lepton-derived and quark-derived quantities tends to import claims we are not making.

\paragraph{Not a derivation.}
We have not derived $\mathcal{F}^2 = m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$ from any Lagrangian, symmetry, or theoretical framework. The observation is post-hoc in the sense that all of $m_e, m_\mu, m_\tau$, and $m_s$ were known when the comparison was made.

\paragraph{Not a prediction.}
The relation was not written down in advance of the strange-quark measurement and then confirmed; the masses involved were already established. We use the language of \emph{compression} (Section~\ref{sec:null_tight}) rather than \emph{prediction} for this reason. The compression claim is independent of authorial chronology: it asks how much the relation reduces the description length of the data, not whether it was anticipated.

\paragraph{Not a mechanism.}
We do not propose a flavor-symmetry mechanism, a modular construction, a flavon alignment, or a grand-unified embedding that would generate $\mathcal{F}^2 = m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$. We do not claim relevance to any specific flavor model. We hand the question of mechanism to model builders without attempting to anticipate their answer.

\paragraph{Not a charm or bottom relation.}
We have examined the analogous question for $m_c$ and $m_b$ and find that no integer power of $\mathcal{F}$ matches either at the natural lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star$ within current lattice precision. The numerical proximity $\mathcal{F}^3 \approx m_c^{\msbar}(m_b)$ noted in earlier drafts of this work requires evaluating $m_c$ at the bottom-quark scale rather than at the natural lepton scale, and so requires a different scale prescription than the strange relation. We do not have a structural justification for that different prescription, and we therefore restrict the present note to the strange sector.

%======================================================================
\section{What it might be}
%======================================================================

We restrict ourselves to one short paragraph of speculation, clearly labeled.

The observation, if it is more than coincidence, suggests one of three possibilities. First, the Koide relation may have a geometric origin that has not been recognized, and the Soddy connection may be its geometric content; in that case the present observation extends the same geometric structure into the strange sector via the natural mass scale of the lepton triple. Second, the lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ may be the natural matching scale of some flavor mechanism that produces $m_s$ from leptonic input, in which case the observation is a constraint that any such mechanism must satisfy. Third, the observation may be a coincidence of the kind that Koide's relation itself might be: an unexplained numerical regularity that nonetheless has remained stable as measurements have improved, and that any future explanation of Koide will eventually need to account for. We do not argue for any of the three.

We note only that the compression figure of $\sim 7.4$ bits (Section~\ref{sec:null_tight}) is large enough that, if the relation were a coincidence, it would be a coincidence requiring explanation in its own right.

%======================================================================
\section*{Computational note}
%======================================================================

All numerical results in this paper are reproducible with the open-source Python code at~\cite{KoideSoddyCode}. Four-loop $\msbar$ running is performed via CRunDec~\cite{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$ and flavor thresholds at $m_c(m_c) = 1.273$~GeV and $m_b(m_b) = 4.183$~GeV. Lepton inputs are PDG~2024 charged-lepton pole masses. Quark inputs are FLAG~2024 $N_f = 2{+}1{+}1$ averages for light quarks and PDG~2024 for heavy quarks. The null-model sampler uses a fixed random seed for reproducibility; sample size is $10^5$ candidate triples for both tight and loose null tests. Total runtime is under three seconds on a laptop.

